{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609297"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:44:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:44:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16092"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16092"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.1,0.05,0.33,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8783"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71576"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8783"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57072"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1636"},{"type":"tags","id":"4135"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"},{"type":"tags","id":"10625"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20976"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71576"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EComplete hydatidiform molar pregnancy is an abnormal form of pregnancy where there is excessive trophoblastic proliferation and no fetal development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic feature of complete molar pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arises from two sperm fertilizing an empty ovum","Contains both maternal and paternal chromosomes","Results from fertilization of normal ovum by abnormal sperm","Shows markedly elevated human chorionic gonadotropin levels","Typically contains some fetal tissue"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EComplete hydatidiform moles characteristically show \u003Cstrong\u003Emarkedly elevated human chorionic gonadotropin levels\u003C/strong\u003E due to proliferating trophoblastic tissue. The absence of fetal tissue and presence of hydropic villi are other key features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArising from two sperm fertilising an empty ovum\u003C/strong\u003E - Complete moles typically arise from a single sperm that fertilises an empty ovum and then duplicates its chromosomes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains both maternal and paternal chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - Complete moles have only paternal chromosomes (46,XX)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResults from fertilization of normal ovum by abnormal sperm\u003C/strong\u003E - The ovum is empty/abnormal, not the sperm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETypically contains some fetal tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - Complete moles have no fetal tissue due to absence of maternal genetic material\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe genetic composition of a complete mole is 46,XX, with all chromosomes being paternal in origin. This occurs when an empty ovum (lacking maternal chromosomes) is fertilised by a haploid sperm that then duplicates its chromosomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complete hydatidiform moles have only paternal chromosomes (46,XX) due to fertilisation of an empty ovum by a single sperm that duplicates.","Complete moles produce markedly elevated human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) levels due to proliferating trophoblastic tissue.","Complete moles show no fetal tissue or embryonic development due to absence of maternal genetic material."],"references":["Cavaliere A, Ermito S, Dinatale A, Pedata R. Management of molar pregnancy. J Prenat Med. 2009 Jan;3(1):15-7. PMID: 22439034; PMCID: PMC3279094.","Chun T, Dickman E. Molar pregnancy. West J Emerg Med. 2010 May;11(2):228. PMID: 20823989; PMCID: PMC2908674.","Ghassemzadeh S, Farci F, Kang M. Hydatidiform Mole. [Updated 2023 May 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459155/","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57072"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16092"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57072"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T16:52:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T21:00:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8783"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71576"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadi